  </p>
  <h4>How different jobs relate to each other</h4>
  <p>
    Jobs can have huge variety in granularity. Many smaller jobs collectively
    do a bigger job. For example, if you have a job of decorating your house,
    there are smaller jobs-to-be-done of hanging pictures, buying furniture,
    knocking down walls, etc.
  </p>
  <p>
    To model this in our heads, we can think of jobs as being nested, in a
    tree-like structure. We can imagine each node representing a “job”. This is
    just an easy way to illustrate hierarchy and parent-child relationships.
    Visualizing our product this way helps us stay focused on what the product is
    and is not, what we should build and what we should not.
  </p>
  <p>
    If we use a tree to diagram the job of “chat” for Slack, you can see that
    Facebook, and Dropbox have a similar child job of chat or conversation, but if
    you follow that child to its parent, the purpose of each of those products are
    all very different.
  </p>
