<div class="text-wrap">
  <h4>The role of the “parent” job</h4>
  <p>
    The parent job (or node) is the larger job that our product is fulfilling; the
    solution that people *actually *want. All child jobs are derived from the
    parent. Child jobs may seem very similar or almost the same across different
    parents, but if we understand the parent-child relationship, we can easily know
    how to stay focused on the parent job we want to succeed with.
  </p>
  <p>
    Child jobs are where we find smaller, more specific jobs like “send data to
    analytics tools” or “reduce Marketing team dependence on developer resources”.
    These are the solutions people *think* they want. Any siblings within our
    parent job is a job for which Segment may want to build a solution.
  </p>
  <p>
    If we use a tree to diagram the job of “chat” for Slack, you can see that
    Facebook, and Dropbox have a similar child job of chat or conversation, but if
    you follow that child to its parent, the purpose of each of those products are
    all very different.
  </p>
<div class="work-image"><img src="/images/portfolio/jbtd/parent-child.png"></div>
</div>


<div class="text-wrap">
  <h4>The role of the “gateway” job</h4>
  <p>
    Each of the “child” jobs have the potential to be what we call “gateways”.
    These are often the product people <em>think</em> they want.
  </p>
  <p>
    Since gateway jobs meet a more narrowly scoped and specific need, they are
    easier to identify with. It is the more tangible version of the problem to
    solve. Because of this, the gateway job can be critical to a potential customer
    or existing customer understanding that a product meets their need—it’s what
    initially draws them to Segment.
  </p>
  <h4>Segment’s parent job</h4>
  <p>
    Not surprisingly, every customer ultimately begins their journey toward
    Segment with the push of needing or wanting to make better decisions based
    on data.
  </p>
  <p>
    What we are calling the “Segment job” is the product we believe people
    <em>actually</em> want.  Using the job-to-be-done statement syntax, the
    Segment job can be expressed as:
  </p>
  <blockquote>
    <p>
      When I want to set myself up to easily make decisions from data, I want to
      eliminate the friction of collecting my data, so I can use it in all the
      places I need it.
    </p>
  </blockquote>
  <h4>Segment’s current gateway job</h4>
  <p>
    If the parent job is the product people actually want, the gateway job is
    the product people think they. Again, using the job-to-be-done statement
    syntax, the Gateway job can be expressed as:
  </p>
  <blockquote>
    <p>
      When I implement an analytics tool, and I realize there are barriers to
      implementing these tools, I want to make the implementation as simple as
      possible, so I can send data to analytics tools with ease.
    </p>
  </blockquote>
  <p>
    The gateway job is where many (not all) of our customers come to know about
    Segment. It is their <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Original_intent">original intent</a>
    and the job that needs to deliver them an excellent experience. Customers who
    have found Segment to successfully solve the problem of Gateway job typically
    go on to find value in Segment above and beyond that.
  </p>
  <p>
    We have an opportunity to surprise and delight our customers when they can find
    more value in the product than they came for. These customers will find new
    ways to use the product within their teams to scale their usage of Segment with
    the needs of their organizations. When these customers are hired to new jobs
    they take Segment with them.
  </p>
